initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, natural language processing (NLP) has been revolutionized by transformer-based neural networks, achieving state-of-the-art results in various tasks. Quantum language models (QLMs) are proposed as a novel generalization to traditional transformer models by leveraging quantum mechanisms. The quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient decoding process in QLMs by reducing the complexity of parallelization from O(n) to O(log(n)). This paper implements and compares both traditional transformer-based models and QLMs by evaluating perplexity and fluency scores on three commonly used text datasets. The datasets include Wikipedia, Twitter, and Reddit. Additionally, the effect of masked language modeling, a popular technique used in traditional NLP to improve language understanding, is also explored in QLMs. Surprisingly, the results showed that masked language modeling didn't improve QLMs performance. The reasons and implications behind this result are discussed, aiming to deepen our understanding of quantum machine learning theory and its potential applications in NLP.

In recent years, generative models of physical systems have been transformed by neural network architectures, achieving breakthroughs in simulation accuracy. Quantum Monte Carlo (QMC) algorithms are proposed as a novel generalization to traditional molecular dynamics simulations by harnessing quantum fluctuations. The quantum effects lead to an efficient sampling process in QMCs by reducing the computational complexity of parallelization from O(n) to O(log(n)). This paper simulates and compares both traditional classical molecular dynamics models and QMCs by evaluating structural accuracy and dynamical scores on three commonly used materials datasets. The datasets include carbon nanotubes, proteins, and nanoparticles. Additionally, the effect of quantum corrections, a popular technique used in traditional condensed matter physics to improve material understanding, is also explored in QMCs. Interestingly, the results showed that quantum corrections didn't enhance QMCs' predictive power. The reasons and implications behind this result are analyzed, aiming to illuminate our comprehension of quantum many-body theory and its potential applications in materials science.
